  "prompt": "Why is the Duronto train green?",
  "response": "The **Duronto Express** trains in India are typically identified by their **green** color, which serves as a visual distinction from other trains. The green color specifically signifies that Duronto trains are **non-stop** (or have very limited stops) and are designed for faster travel between major cities. This color scheme helps passengers and railway staff easily identify the train category.\n\nHere are a few reasons why Duronto trains are green:\n\n1. **Distinct Identity**: The green color distinguishes Duronto trains from other categories like Rajdhani (blue), Shatabdi (red and white), and other passenger trains.\n   \n2. **Non-Stop Service**: Duronto trains are known for their non-stop or limited-stop services, and the color serves as a quick visual cue for this feature.\n\n3. **Branding**: Indian Railways uses color-coding as part of its branding strategy to differentiate train types based on speed, service, and purpose.\n\n4. **Efficient Communication**: The green color helps passengers, platform staff, and railway personnel quickly identify Duronto trains, ensuring smooth operations and boarding processes.\n\nIn summary, the green color of Duronto trains is a deliberate choice by Indian Railways to signify its unique non-stop service and to make it easily distinguishable from other train categories.",
